                    {
                        "id": 15789,
                        "title": "Maximum support to be collected thru int’l donors meet taking donors into confidence",
                        "content": "<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.newsnrn.com/wp-content/uploads/ram-sharan1.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-15790\" src=\"http://www.newsnrn.com/wp-content/uploads/ram-sharan1-256x300.jpg\" alt=\"ram-sharan1\" width=\"256\" height=\"300\" /></a>The government aims to mobilize the maximum cooperation in the International Donors Conference for the post-earthquake reconstruction. The donors’ conference is scheduled for June 25.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The government has constituted a conference preparation committee under the coordination of Finance Minister Dr Ram Sharan Mahat. The committee says it is working at a war footing in preparation for the conference and the preparations have reached the final stages.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Minister Dr Mahat said the Post-Disaster Needs Assessment (PDNA) report would be presented and a high-level mechanism would be set up to take forward the post-quake reconstruction, rehabilitation and rebuilding works in a transparent manner and the utilization of the assistance, adding that the donors would be thus taken into confidence.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Talking to the National News Agency (RSS), the Finance Minister said efforts would be made to take grant from the donors as far as possible and if not concessional loan. He made it clear that the government would not take conditional loan.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The government will assure the donors of the transparency in the aid expenditure explaining them that the expenses would be audited by the Office of the Comptroller General and also monitored by the Legislature-Parliament.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">“Invitation along with the PDNA report to be presented in the conference have been sent to various countries and agencies. The entire programme and the agenda for June 25 conference has been completed. Arrangements have also been made regarding the hotels where the guests would be staying as well as the security matters,” Dr Mahat said.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The donors would be shown around the earthquake-affected areas a day before the conference. Similarly, the donors would be given a real glimpse of the damage caused by the devastating earthquake by means of a documentary depicting the major destinations of the country before and after the earthquake which would be shown during the conference.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Minister for Foreign Affairs Mahendra Bahadur Pandey said the government has already invited 62 countries and donor agencies for their participation, adding that his ministry was carrying out the required works in close coordination with the Ministry of Finance.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">He said, “The donor agencies’ conference had to be convened as it would not be possible to rebuild and recover the damage caused to the physical infrastructure through own resources.”</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Minister Pandey hoped all the programmes would be concluded on a single day as the discussions would be focused on the main agenda aimed at making the conference organized to collect financial support necessary for reconstruction fruitful.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The other objective of the conference is to deliver positive message that most of the touristic destinations were not damaged and infrastructures are also safe from the devastating quake.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">National Planning Commission (NPC) Vice-chairman Dr Govinda Pokhrel said that the PDNA report would convince the foreign donors to support Nepal as it was prepared by following international procedures based on reality. He added that all things should not be expected from the conference though they have pointed out the need of Rs 666 billion fund for the reconstruction operations.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dr Pokhrel further added that all expectations would not be fulfilled only from the conference itself as the budgetary system in Nepal and foreign countries are based on different modality, however they could express their commitment to support the reconstruction projects in the conference.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">NPC Vice-chair Pokhrel said that the reconstruction projects could be launched if they got financial support to be needed for five years from neighbouring countries and development partners.\r\nPrior to this, the government has set up a reconstruction fund of Rs 200 billion and government itself has deposited Rs 20 billion so far and has expected to collect remaining funds from donors.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Though, the government so far has not formed a high level mechanism to operate the reconstruction projects, it is in progress, it is learnt.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The foreign donors may draw their attentions in its mechanism expecting a high level reconstruction authority. However, the NPC has already suggested the government to form a National Resettlement, New-construction Implementation Committee on the chairmanship of the Prime Minister.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As per the NPC report, other members of the commission are Ministers for Home Affairs, Finance and Urban Development, NPC Vice-chairman, chief secretary and Chief of Army Staff.</p>",
                        "img": "http://www.newsnrn.com/wp-content/uploads/ram-sharan1.jpg",
                        "date": "2015-06-18 09:57:06",
                        "link": "http://www.newsnrn.com/api/public/v1/news/15789"
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 15746,
                        "title": "वैदेशिक रोजगारी नि: शुल्क",
                        "content": "<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>निर्णय कायान्वय गर्न प्रधानमन्त्रीको निर्देशन</strong>\r\nप्रधानमन्त्री सुशील कोइरालाले मलेसियासहित खाडीका पाँच मुलुकमा रोजगारीका लागि जाने नेपाली कामदारसँग शुल्क लिन नपाउने निर्णय कडाईका साथ लागू गर्न निर्देशन दिएका छन्।</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.newsnrn.com/wp-content/uploads/malesiya_qualalampur_607272178_144852612_267604696_872902432.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-15747\" src=\"http://www.newsnrn.com/wp-content/uploads/malesiya_qualalampur_607272178_144852612_267604696_872902432.jpg\" alt=\"malesiya_qualalampur_607272178_144852612_267604696_872902432\" width=\"820\" height=\"520\" /></a></p>\r\nकेही वैदेशिक रोजगार व्यवसायीले नि:शुल्क कामदार पठाउने श्रम मन्त्रालयको निर्णयको विरोध गरेपछि प्रधानन्त्री सुशील कोइरालाले मंगलबार श्रम राज्य मन्त्री टेकबहादुर गुरुङ, गभर्नर चिरञ्जीवी नेपाल र लोकतान्त्रिक वैदशिक रोजगार व्यवसायीलाई छलफलका लागि बोलाएर यस्तो निर्देशन दिएका हुन्।\r\n\r\nनि:शुल्क भिसा र टिकटमा विदेश पठाउने निर्णय राम्रो भएको भन्दै त्यसको तत्काल कार्यान्वयन गर्न प्रधानमन्त्रीले निर्देशन दिनुभयो, बैठकमा सहभागी गभर्नर नेपालले अन्नपूर्णसँग भने, यसमा व्यवसायीको पनि विरोध थिएन।\r\n\r\nश्रम राज्य मन्त्री गुरुङले एक हप्ताअघि मन्त्रीस्तरीय बैठकबाट कतार, युएई, बहराईन, ओमान, साउदी अरेबिया र मलेसियामा रोजगारीमा जानेसँग वैदेशिक रोजगार व्यवसायीले शुल्क लिन नपाउने निर्णय गराएका थिए।\r\n\r\nमन्त्रालयको उक्त निर्णयको विरोध गर्दै केही व्यवसायीले मन्त्रालयको निर्णय फिर्ता गराउन चौतर्फी दबाब दिँदै आएका थिए। यसअघि ती मुलुकमा रोजगारीका लागि पठाउँदा कामदारबाट लाख रुपैयाँ लिने वैदेसिक रोजागार व्यवसायीले अब श्रम खर्च, विमान र न्यून सेवा शुल्कबाहेक टिकट र भिसाको रकम लिन नपाउने भएका हुन्।\r\n\r\nमन्त्री गुरुङले लाख रुपैयाँ खर्च गरेर विदेश जानुपर्ने बाध्यतालाई कम गर्न यस्तो निर्णय गरेको छलफलमा जानकारी दिएका थिए।\r\n\r\nतीन महिनाअघि कतारका श्रम मन्त्रीको नेपाल भ्रमणका बेला आफूहरूले नेपाली कामदारसँग कुनै शुल्क नलिएको खुलासा गरेपछि मन्त्री गुरुङले बिनाशुल्क रोजगारीमा विदेश पठाउने तयारी थालेका हुन्।\r\n\r\nत्यसपछि उनले मन्त्रीस्तरीय निर्णयबाटै नेपाली कामदार बढी भएका ६ मुलुकमा भिसा र टिकटको बाहेक शुल्क लिन नपाउने निर्णय गरेका हुन्।\r\n\r\nसरकारको यस्तो निर्णयपछि म्यानपावर व्यवसायीले अनावश्यक रकम उठाउन नपाउने भएपछि विरोध थालेका हुन्। व्यवसायीले श्रम मन्त्रालयको निर्णय राम्रो भएपनि केही समय पर सार्न आग्रह गरेका थिए।\r\n\r\nउनीहरूले कतिपय मुलुकमा पहिलानै भिसा सम्झौता भैसकेकाले कामदारसँग शुल्क लिन पाउनुपर्ने माग गर्दै आएका थिए। प्रधानमन्त्रीसँगको बैठकमा मलेसिया जाने कामदारलाई बायोम्याट्रिक प्रणाली लागू गर्ने विषयमा पनि छलफल भएको थियो।\r\n\r\nमलेसियासँग श्रम सम्झौता हुँदै\r\nसरकारले नेपाली कामदार बढी भएको मलेसियासँग द्विपक्षीय श्रम सम्झौता गर्ने भएको छ।\r\n\r\nद्विपक्षीय श्रम सम्झौता गरेर कामदार पठाउँदा कामदारको शोषण भए वा अन्य समस्यामा परे दुवै देशका सरकार जिम्मेवार हुने भएकाले यस्तो तयारी गरिएको हो।\r\n\r\nमलेसियासँग श्रम सम्झौता गर्न श्रम मन्त्री गुरुङ छिट्टै क्वालालम्पुर जाने भएका छन्। श्रम राज्य मन्त्रीको मलेसिया भ्रमण स्वीकृतिका लागि अर्थ मन्त्रालयमा फाइल पेश गरिएको छ।\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">यो समाचार अन्नपुर्ण पोष्टको हो |</p>",
                        "img": "http://www.newsnrn.com/wp-content/uploads/malesiya_qualalampur_607272178_144852612_267604696_872902432.jpg",
                        "date": "2015-06-18 04:30:57",
                        "link": "http://www.newsnrn.com/api/public/v1/news/15746"
